==Economy==
[[Image:BAE Systems, Chadderton.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A three-storey building composed of glass windows and grey concrete stands across from a tarmac road and in front of a clear blue sky. A road passing horizontally in the foreground is divided by a pavement and metal barriers. The building's entrance appears central and is flanked by mirrored-glass windows and is marked by a red sign with the text BAE SYSTEMS.|[[BAE Systems]] have a manufacturing plant in south Chadderton. The plant occupies the former [[Avro]] aircraft factory which produced over 3,000 [[Avro Lancaster]] bombers during the [[World War II|Second World War]].]]
Up until the 18th century, the inhabitants of Chadderton raised domestic farm animals, supplementing their incomes by the spinning and weaving wool in the [[domestic system]]. Primitive [[coal mining]] was established by the 17th century, and the [[factory system]] adopted in the late-18th century.<ref name="Plan"/> During the [[Victorian era]], Chadderton's economy was heavily dependent on manufacturing industries, especially the spinning of cotton, but also the weaving of silk and production of hats.<ref name="Top of England"/><ref name="Chadderton8"/> By the 20th century the landscape was covered with over 50 [[cotton mill]]s.<ref name="Plan"/> Industries ancillary to these sectors, including coal mining, brick making, mechanical engineering and bleaching and dyeing were present.<ref name="Chadderton8"/> Chadderton developed an extensive coal mining sector auxiliary to Chadderton's cotton industry and workforce. Coal was transported out of the township via the [[Rochdale Canal]]. The amount of coal was overestimated however, and production began to decline even before that of the local spinning industry; Chadderton's last coal mine closed in 1920.<ref name="Looking45">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|p=45}}.</ref> 

Since the [[deindustrialisation]] of the region in the mid-20th century, these industries have been replaced by newer sectors and industries,<ref name="Chadderton8"/> although many of the civic developments that accompanied industrialisation remain in the form of public buildings; a town hall, public baths and library.<ref name="Plan"/> The few surviving cotton mills are now occupied by warehousing and distribution companies, or used as space for light industry.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|O'Rourke|Portland|2004|p=117}}.</ref>

British aircraft manufacturer [[Avro]] built a factory in south Chadderton in 1938<U+2013>39.<ref name="Chadderton8"/><ref name="Strat">{{Harvnb|Stratton|Trinder|2000|p=76}}.</ref> It was one of the largest employers in the area, producing a variety of aircraft models including [[Avro Anson|Ansons]], [[Avro Manchester|Manchesters]] and [[Bristol Blenheim]]s.<ref name="Strat"/> During the [[World War II|Second World War]], 3,050 [[Avro Lancaster]] bombers were built at the Chadderton factory<U+2014>over 40&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of the [[Royal Air Force]]'s fleet.<ref name="Chadderton8"/><ref name="SpinWeb"/> After the [[Aircraft and Shipbuilding Industries Act 1977]], Avro became part of the nationalised [[British Aerospace]] (now [[BAE Systems]]) and produced commercial aircraft for [[Boeing]] and [[Airbus]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo040226/halltext/40226h01.htm|publisher=parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk|title=Commons Hansard: 26 Feb 2004 : Column 154WH|date=2004-02-26|accessdate=2008-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/1700-jobs-axed-as-bae-quits-the-regional-aircraft-industry-618326.html|publisher=independent.co.uk|title=1,700 jobs axed as BAE quits the regional aircraft industry|first=Michael|last=Harrison|date=2001-11-28|accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> 

Chadderton has been described as a "relatively prosperous town [...] which makes it a popular residential area".<ref name="Plan"/> Chadderton Mall is a shopping precinct located in the town centre, and is one of Chadderton's main concentrations of retailing. It was constructed in 1974, and opened in 1975. It includes an [[Asda]] supermarket and a variety of smaller shops.<ref name="Chadderton38">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=38}}.</ref> [[The Stationery Office]] has a base in Chadderton, as does [[3M]]. In 2008, 3M was the centre of a high profile robbery of over 3,000 [[British passport]]s.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/thousands-of-passports-and-visas-stolen-from-van-880313.html|publisher=independent.co.uk|title=Thousands of passports and visas stolen from van|accessdate=2009-01-02|date=2008-06-30|last=McSmith|first=Andy}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/12271/3000-passports-stolen-from-van|publisher=oldham-chronicle.co.uk|title=3,000 passports stolen from van|date=2008-07-29|last=Barker|first=Janice|accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article4435145.ece|publisher=timesonline.co.uk|date=2008-07-31|accessdate=2009-01-02|title=Passport theft police 'arrest delivery man'|first=Marcus |last=Leroux | location=London}}</ref> Other major businesses include [[Costco]] and [[Shop Direct Group]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://archive.thisislancashire.co.uk/2004/6/16/484938.html|title=Workers shocked as 475 jobs are axed|publisher=thisislancashire.co.uk|date=2004-06-16|accessdate=2008-12-26}}</ref> The Centre (formerly Elk Mill Retail Park),<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/522891_new_superstore_has_everything__but_food|title=New superstore has everything <U+2013> but food|date=2007-01-31|accessdate=2008-07-27|publisher=[[Oldham Advertiser|oldhamadvertiser.co.uk]]}}</ref> is a [[retail park]] located at the start of the [[A627(M) motorway]].<ref name="OldhamBusMap"/>

==Landmarks==
Chadderton Town Hall was the seat of Chadderton Urban District Council. It is Chadderton's second [[town hall]], the first was the former Chadderton Lyceum building (demolished in 1975).<ref name="Looking31"/> The current town hall, Chadderton's first purpose built municipal building, was designed by Taylor and Simister of Oldham, and was opened in 1913 by Herbert Wolstencroft [[Justice of the Peace|JP]], the then [[chairman]] of Chadderton Urban District Council.<ref name="Looking31"/> The architectural style was intended to have "a broad and strong treatment of the [[English Renaissance]]".<ref name="Looking31"/> It features "charming gardens and a beautifully renovated ballroom".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/az_of_services/cs-chadderton-town-hall.htm|publisher=oldham.gov.uk|accessdate=2008-12-20|title=Chadderton Town Hall|author=Oldham Council}}</ref> Since 2007, Chadderton Town Hall has housed the Oldham Register Office, the [[civil registration]] authority for the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/529847_wedding_bells_ring_out_again|publisher=oldhamadvertiser.co.uk|date=2007-07-04|accessdate=2008-12-20|title=Wedding bells ring out again|first=Stuart|last=Greer}}</ref><ref name="ORO">{{citation |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/living/births_marriages_and_deaths.htm|publisher=oldham.gov.uk|author=Oldham Council|title=Births, Marriages and Deaths|accessdate=2008-12-20}}</ref> It is a licensed venue for marriage ceremonies, and holds records of births, marriages and deaths which have taken place in what is now the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham from 1837 to the present.<ref name="ORO"/>

[[Image:Foxdenton Hall.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A two-storey brick-built mansion in its own well-kept garden of green grass. The ground floor has six windows - three on each side of a wooden front door. The second floor has seven windows. The house has a grey slate roof surmounted by two small brick chimneys. Behind the house are leafless trees and behind those, a clear blue sky.|The [[Grade II* listed buildings in Greater Manchester|Grade II* listed building]] 18th-century Foxdenton Hall, a former [[manor house]] and [[mansion]], with public gardens. It has been fully restored.]]
Foxdenton Hall is a two-storey [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] [[mansion]] and former [[manor house]], with an [[Brickwork|English garden wall bond]] exterior and its own private gardens.<ref name="Image"/> The original Hall was erected in the mid-15th century as a home for the Radclyffes, who had acquired the title of joint [[Lord of the Manor|Lords of the Manor]] with the Asshetons of Chadderton, through marriage. This Foxdenton Hall was demolished to make way for a second Hall, built in 1620. The ground floor of that second Hall now forms the basement of the present Hall, built in 1700.<ref name="Looking12">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|p=12}}.</ref> The building is described as "a dignified early Georgian house, particularly rare in this part of the country".<ref name="Image">{{citation |title=Foxdenton Hall |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=212409 |publisher=imagesofengland.org.uk|author=National Monuments Record|authorlink=National Monuments Record|work=[[Images of England]]|accessdate=2008-02-24 }}</ref> The Radclyffes moved out of Foxdenton Hall in the late 18th century, favouring properties they had purchased in [[Dorset]], although they still maintained ownership.<ref name="Looking12"/> Foxdenton Hall and the adjoining Foxdenton Park were leased to Chadderton Council by the Radclyffes in 1922, when they opened to the public. In 1960 the council took over ownership of the Hall, by which time it was in a state of disrepair. Following protest about funding and the condition of the building, Foxdenton Hall was restored in 1965.<ref name="Looking13">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|p=13}}.</ref>

Chadderton War Memorial is located outside Chadderton Town Hall, and was originally erected "in honour of the men of Chadderton who made the supreme sacrifice and in grateful remembrance of all who served their county"  during the [[First World War]], but later, the [[Second World War]].<ref name="Chadderton War Memorial"/> It is a [[granite]] [[obelisk]] fronted by three steps. At the front on a short plinth stands a [[bronze]] figure of an ordinary soldier, holding a rifle in his right hand.<ref name="Chadderton War Memorial"/> It was designed by Taylor and Simister and sculpted by [[Albert Toft]].<ref name="Chadderton War Memorial"/> Chadderton War Memorial was commissioned by the Chadderton War Memorial Committee and unveiled on 8 October 1921 by Councillor Ernest Kempsey.<ref name="Chadderton War Memorial">{{citation |url=http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/MR/MR-OLD25.htm |title= Chadderton War Memorial |author=[[Public Monuments and Sculpture Association]]|date=2003-06-16 |accessdate=2008-12-22}}</ref>

[[Chadderton Hall Park]] is a public park by the [[River Irk]] in the north of Chadderton, spanning an area of over {{convert|15|acre|ha|0}},<ref name="Green">{{citation |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080207083531/http://www.greenflagaward.org.uk/winners/GSP001243/|publisher=greenflagaward.org.uk|author=[[Green Flag Award]]|title=Chadderton Hall Park|accessdate=2010-01-28|work=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> in what were once the gardens of the manorial Chadderton Hall. At the end of the 19th century they were leased to Joseph Ball, who transformed the hall and grounds into a pleasure garden, complete with a boating lake and a [[menagerie]].<ref name="Looking9-10">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|pp=9-10}}.</ref> The hall was demolished in 1939. The park is now owned by Oldham Council, the [[local authority]], and was opened to the public in 1956. It was awarded [[Green Flag Award|Green Flag]] status in 2006.<ref name="Green"/><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldhamparks.co.uk/awards|publisher=oldhamparks.co.uk|title=Awards|accessdate=2008-12-23}}</ref>

==Transport==
[[Image:Canal and Motorway, Chadderton.png|thumb|right|alt=View from a bridge over a canal, with a motorway running to the left. The sky is dark and overcast.|For a short distance in south Chadderton, the [[Rochdale Canal]] and [[M60 motorway]] run in parallel.]]
[[Public transport]] in Chadderton is co-ordinated by the [[Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive]] (GMPTE), a county-wide public body with direct operational responsibilities such as supporting (and in some cases running) local bus services, and managing [[integrated ticketing]] in Greater Manchester. Major [[A roads in Great Britain|A roads]] link Chadderton with other settlements, including the [[A663 road]]. Opened by [[Wilfrid William Ashley, 1st Baron Mount Temple]] in 1925, the arterial A663, named Broadway, bisects Chadderton from north to south, and was "a major factor in the unification and modernisation of the town".<ref name="Chadderton8"/> The [[A669 road]], routed through Chadderton, connects Oldham with Middleton. At its eastern end is Chadderton's town centre.<ref name="OldhamBusMap">{{citation |title=Network Maps: Oldham|url=http://www.gmpte.com/pdfmaps/network/9_oldham.pdf|accessdate=2010-01-28|publisher=gmpte.com
|author=[[Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive]]|year=2010|format=PDF}}</ref> The [[M62 motorway]] runs to the north of the area and is accessed via Broadway at junction 21 and junction 20 via the [[A627(M) motorway]], which terminates at Chadderton's northeastern boundary with Royton.<ref name="OldhamBusMap"/> The [[M60 motorway]] skirts the south of Chadderton, near [[Hollinwood, Greater Manchester|Hollinwood]].<ref name="Plan"/> The section of the M60 through Chadderton was opened in autumn 2000.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|O'Rourke|Portland|2004|p=12}}.</ref>

There are no railway stations in Chadderton. The nearest are [[Mills Hill railway station]] and [[Oldham Werneth railway station]], both part of the [[Oldham Loop Line]], and each just outside the boundaries of Chadderton, in Middleton and Oldham respectively. The [[Middleton Junction and Oldham Branch Railway]] was routed through Chadderton, and [[Middleton Junction railway station]] was within the town limits. It was opened in 1842 for use by the Chadderton Goods Yard to transport fabic and coal in and out of the area, but  closed in 1966 owing to the [[Beeching Axe]].<ref name="Looking38-39">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|pp=38<U+2013>39}}.</ref> Electric [[tram]]ways to and from Middleton opened in 1902. Tram services ran along Middleton Road and terminated in Chadderton. The final tram ran in 1935.<ref name="Looking38-39"/> The Oldham Loop Line is planned to close as a heavy rail line, and reopen in around 2012 as part of a new [[Manchester Metrolink]] light-rail line from [[Manchester Victoria station|Manchester Victoria]] to [[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]] via Oldham. [[South Chadderton Metrolink station]] and [[Freehold Metrolink station]] will open as part of the conversion to Metrolink.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/Oldham_Rochdale.html|publisher=lrta.org ork|title=Manchester to Oldham and Rochdale|author=Light Rail Transit Association|date=2007-11-24|accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.metrolink.co.uk/futuremetrolink/oldham_rochdale_line.asp|publisher=gmpte.com|author=Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive|authorlink=Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive|accessdate=2009-09-11|title=Oldham Rochdale line}}</ref>

The majority of the bus services in Chadderton are operated by [[First Manchester]], who provide frequent services to [[Middleton, Greater Manchester|Middleton]], Oldham and [[Shaw and Crompton|Shaw]], with other services running to Manchester, Royton, Rochdale and the [[Trafford Centre]]. [[Bluebird Bus & Coach|Bluebird]] run services in Chadderton and provide links to Cheetham Hill, Hollinwood, Moston, New Moston, Newton Heath and Woodhouses.<ref name="OldhamBusMap" /> [[Citibus tours|Citibus]] was a Chadderton-based commercial bus operator serving Greater Manchester, launched in 1986. It competed with GMPTE until 1995 when it was bought-out by [[GM Buses|GM Buses North]], what is now First Manchester.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gmts.co.uk/explore/history/transport.html#dereg|publisher=gmts.co.uk|title=Deregulated Bus Operators: 1986 onwards|accessdate=2010-01-24|author=Greater Manchester Transport Society|authorlink=Museum of Transport in Manchester|year=2007}}</ref>
<!---ROCHDALE CANAL??? --->

==Education==
{{further|[[List of schools in Oldham]]}}
An old style [[grammar school]] at Healds Green in Chadderton was built and founded in 1789.<ref name="Looking24">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|p=24}}.</ref> As the population of Chadderton grew during the 19th century, more schools were opened, each linked with a local church.<ref name="Top of England"/> Mills Hill School began as a voluntary aided school belonging to the local [[Baptist]] church.<ref name="Looking24"/> Further schoolrooms from this period were found at Cowhill Methodist Church and Washbrook Methodist Church, opened in 1855 and 1893 respectively.<ref name="Looking22">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|p=22}}.</ref> 

The Chadderton Grammar School was the first new style co-educational grammar school opened by [[Lancashire County Council]]. It was opened by [[David Lindsay, 28th Earl of Crawford]], on 18&nbsp;October 1930.<ref name="Looking24"/><ref name="Chadderton25"/> In 1959, it became The Girls' Grammar, when a separate school for boys was opened. The Girls' Grammar briefly became Mid-Chadderton School, what is now [[The Radclyffe School]], and the boys' school part of [[North Chadderton School]].<ref name="Looking24"/><ref name="Chadderton25">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=25}}.</ref> Radclyffe, North Chadderton and [[South Chadderton School]]s are the town's three co-educational, non-denominational, comprehensive [[secondary school]]s.<ref name="Plan"/> North Chadderton School has a [[sixth form college]] for 16<U+2013>19 year-olds. The Radclyffe School, which has specialist [[Technology College]] status, was modernised in 2008 by way of a <U+00A3>30&nbsp;million new school complex opened by Sir [[Alex Ferguson]] on 8&nbsp;July 2008.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/1057493_fergies_fan_club|publisher=oldhamadvertiser.co.uk|title=Fergie<U+2019>s fan club|date=2008-07-09|accessdate=2008-12-21}}</ref> South Chadderton is the smallest of the three secondaries, with about 700&nbsp;pupils.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/download/(id)/82229/(as)/105733_300475.pdf|publisher=ofsted.gov.uk|accessdate=2009-09-14|title=South Chadderton School: Inspection report|format=PDF|author=OFSTED|authorlink=Office for Standards in Education, Children's Services and Skills|date=2007-04-20}}</ref>

==Religion==
{{seealso|List of churches in Greater Manchester}}
[[Image:St Mark's Church, Chadderton.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An angular taupe-coloured church on a bright sunny day. The church fills the image with the exception of a flat piece of green grass and grey pavement at the church's entrance and the dark green silhouette of trees along the left of the picture. The single-storey church has many small slitted triangular and rectangular windows across its fa<U+00E7>ade, except for a dark rectangular entrance in which a man stands. At the far end of the church is a triangular spire standing tall and bold against a light blue sky at around six or seven times the height of a man.|The [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] Parish Church of St Mark was built between 1960 and 1963. It is one of several churches serving Chadderton and is a Grade II [[listed building]].]]
[[Image:Healds Green Methodist Church.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An orange-brick church perched on a shallow hillside in a daytime scene in which the sky appears white. The triangular stone windows of the two-storey church are clear, as are the grounds in the church's proximity. The grounds are composed of green grass, light grey stone pathways, brown brick fencing and green trees overhanging the church.|Healds Green Methodist Church at Chadderton Fold was founded in 1865.]]
Chadderton had no medieval church of its own,<ref name="Chadderton85">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=85}}.</ref> and until 1541, for ecclesiastical purposes, lay within the parish of [[Prestwich-cum-Oldham]] in the [[Diocese of Lichfield]].  The diocese was then divided, and Chadderton became part of the [[Diocese of Chester]].<ref name="ChadRoy1932"/> This in turn was divided in 1847, when the present [[Anglican Diocese of Manchester|Diocese of Manchester]] was created. For ritual baptisms, marriages and burials, the people of Chadderton, a [[Christianity|Christian]] community, had to travel to churches that lay outside of the township's boundaries, including [[Oldham Parish Church|Oldham St Mary's]], [[Church of St Leonard, Middleton|Middleton St Leonard's]], and [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Prestwich|Prestwich St Mary's]].  The route of some of the ancient paths to these churches is preserved in the modern layout of some of the town's roads.<ref name="Chadderton15">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=15}}.</ref>

The [[New Parishes Act 1844]] allowed for the creation of a parish for Chadderton, dedicated to St [[Matthew the Evangelist]]. Services were initially held in the stables of Chadderton Hall, and then in a temporary wooden structure opened in 1848.<ref name="Looking20-21">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|pp=20-21}}.</ref><ref name="churchhistory">{{citation |url=http://www.stmatthew-stlukechadderton.org.uk/articles.php?lng=en&pg=32|publisher=stmatthew-stlukechadderton.org.uk|accessdate=2008-11-06|title=History - St Matthew}}</ref> The Church of St Matthew was opened for the parish in 1857 by the then [[Bishop of Manchester]], [[James Prince Lee]].<ref name="Looking20-21"/><ref name="churchhistory"/> A [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] was added in 1881.<ref name="Looking20-21"/> Following the construction of this church, four followed. There are now several Anglican parishes, and within them daughter and mission churches, serving the town.<ref name="Chadderton85"/> The parish of St Matthew united with the neighbouring parish of St Luke, and the United Benefice of St Matthew with St Luke now lies within the Tandle [[Deanery]] of the Diocese of Manchester.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.manchester.anglican.org/churches/rochdale-archdeaconry/tandle|publisher=manchester.anglican.org|author=[[Anglican Diocese of Manchester]]|accessdate=2008-11-05|title=Tandle Deanery}}</ref> Also within this deanery is the Parish Church of St Mark, built in the early&nbsp;1960s. It is a blue brick building with a graduated slate pitched roof, and a rectangular brick steeple with a high gabled roof.<ref name="Image2">{{citation |title=Church of St Mark, Milne Street|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=470603&mode=quick |publisher=imagesofengland.org.uk|author=National Monuments Record|authorlink=National Monuments Record|work=[[Images of England]]|accessdate=2008-12-22 }}</ref> It was granted Grade II [[listed building]] status in 1998.<ref name="Image2"/>

In addition to the [[Church of England]], a variety of [[List of Reformed churches|Reformed denominations]] have been practiced in Chadderton. [[Nonconformism]] was popular in Chadderton, and places of worship for [[Methodism]], [[Baptist]] and [[Congregationalism]] were built during the 19th and 20th&nbsp;centuries.<ref name="Chadderton85"/> Washbrook Methodist Church and School at Butler Green was built in 1868, but was demolished around&nbsp;1970.<ref name="Looking22-23">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1990|pp=22-23}}.</ref>

Chadderton forms part of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Salford]]. The [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] Parish of Corpus Christi was founded in Chadderton in 1878, following immigration to the region by Irish Catholics fleeing the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]]. A combined school and church was opened in 1904.<ref name="Chadderton90"/> A further Catholic parish for Chadderton, dedicated to [[Saint Herbert]], was created in 1916.<ref name="Chadderton90">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=90}}.</ref> Its first [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] was held on 1&nbsp;July&nbsp;1916, the day the [[Battle of the Somme]] began.<ref name="Chadderton90"/>

==Sports==
[[Chadderton F.C.]] is an [[association football]] club formed in 1947 under the name Millbrow Football Club, later changing to North Chadderton Amateurs, before adopting its present name in 1957.<ref name="ChadFC">{{citation |url=http://www.chaddertonfc.org.uk/pages.php?page_id=329|publisher=chaddertonfc.org.uk|title=Club History|accessdate=2010-01-22}}</ref> It plays in the [[North West Counties Football League First Division]]. Past players have included former [[England national football team]] captain [[David Platt (footballer)|David Platt]], former [[Leeds United A.F.C.]] and [[Crystal Palace F.C.]] player [[John Pemberton (footballer)|John Pemberton]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team]] player [[Steve Jones (Northern Irish footballer)|Steve Jones]].<ref name="ChadFC"/> [[Mark Owen]] of pop group [[Take That]] briefly played for the club.<ref name="ChadFC"/> Chaddertonians A.F.C. were formed in 1937 and currently play in the [[Lancashire Amateur League]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.clubwebsite.co.uk/chaddertoniansafc/|publisher=clubwebsite.co.uk|accessdate=2008-12-22|title=Chaddertonians AFC|date=2008-12-20}}</ref> Chadderton Park F.C. is an amateur football club founded in 1977.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.chaddertonparkfc.co.uk/about.htm|publisher=chaddertonparkfc.co.uk|accessdate=2008-12-22|title=The History of Chadderton Park Juniors Football Club}}</ref>

The [[Art Nouveau]] Chadderton Baths was a public swimming facility opened in 1937.<ref name="Plan"/> [[Henry Taylor (swimmer)|Henry Taylor]], the [[Great Britain at the Olympics|British Olympic]] [[freestyle swimming]] triple gold medallist and champion was an attendant at Chadderton Baths where many of his awards were displayed.<ref name="Chronicle">{{citation |title=Another 24 hours, another Olympic record |work=[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]] |author=Janice Barker |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/13085/another-24-hours-another-olympic-record |date=2008-08-20|accessdate=2008-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Henry<U+2019>s record still stands |work=[[Manchester Evening News]] |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/1063416_henrys_record_still_stands |date=2008-08-20 |accessdate=2008-08-28}}</ref> Chadderton Baths were closed indefinitely in 2006 after a structural survey found faults which could have put the public at risk.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/516971_is_this_the_end_for_chadderton_baths|title=Is this the end for Chadderton baths?|first=Lee|last=Sykes|date=2006-08-30|accessdate=2008-12-23| publisher=oldhamadvertiser.co.uk}}</ref> Chadderton Sports Centre was built into the baths complex, and had a 50 station gymnasium and dance studio.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ocll.co.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=cms.ShowPage&PageID=11|publisher=ocll.co.uk|author=Oldham Community Leisure|title=Chadderton Sports Centre|accessdate=2008-12-23}}</ref> It closed in December 2009, replaced by the Chadderton Health and Wellbeing Centre, a multi-purpose facility with a new swimming pool, dance studio, library, gym, meeting rooms, caf<U+00E9> and a community police hub.<ref>{{citation |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080314195134/http://www.oldham.gov.uk/community/sport_and_leisure/chadderton_health_and_well-being_centre.htm|publisher=oldham.gov.uk|author=Oldham Council|authorlink=Metropolitan Borough of Oldham|title=Chadderton Health and Well being Centre |accessdate=2009-09-11}}</ref>

==Public services==
[[Image:Chadderton Police Station.jpg|thumb|right|alt=The front of a red-brick two-storey structure that is viewed from the ground upwards. It has a complex facade of four Dutch gables with many windows at regular intervals.|The original Chadderton Police Station on Victoria Street. [[Greater Manchester Police]] now use a newer building at Broadgate in southern Chadderton.]]
[[Image:Chadderton Power Station.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Three massive grey-taupe coloured funnels dominate the scene in which there is a flat piece of green grass in the foreground, red-brick housing in the midground, and behind them in the background the industrial funnels against a white sky. The funnels appear three or four times the size of the row of terraced properties in the midground, and stand independently of each other. Associated with them are two chimneys standing at similar height and a control building in the hazey distance.|[[Chadderton Power Station]] opened in 1955 and was demolished in 1986.]]
Policing in Chadderton is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Police]]. The force's "(Q) Division" has its headquarters for policing the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham in central Oldham. Greater Manchester Police have two stations in Chadderton: a Victorian building in central Chadderton, and a modern purpose-built station at Broadgate in southern Chadderton.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gmpa.gov.uk/oldham.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=gmpa.gov.uk|author=Greater Manchester Police Authority|accessdate=2008-12-21|title=Local Policing in Oldham 2007-2008}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/live/nhoodv3.nsf/index-communities.html?ReadForm&Division=Oldham&Area=Chadderton|publisher=gmp.police.uk|author=Greater Manchester Police|authorlink=Greater Manchester Police|accessdate=2009-09-11|title=Your Neighbourhood Area Policing Team}}</ref> Statutory emergency fire and rescue service is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]], who have a fire station in Chadderton, on Broadway.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/oldham/chadderton-fire-station.aspx|publisher=manchesterfire.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]]|accessdate=2008-12-26|title=Chadderton Fire Station}}</ref>

There are no hospitals in Chadderton&mdash;the nearest are in the larger settlements of Oldham and Rochdale&mdash;but some local health care is provided by Chadderton Town and South Chadderton health centres which are commissioned by NHS Oldham. The [[North West Ambulance Service]] provides emergency patient transport in the area. Other forms of [[health care]] are provided for locally by several small specialist clinics and surgeries.

[[Waste management]] is co-ordinated by the [[local authority]] via the [[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/|title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority (GMWDA)|publisher=gmwda.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]]|year=2008|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> Locally produced [[inert waste]] for disposal is sent to [[landfill]] at the Beal Valley.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/minerals-waste.htm|title=Minerals and Waste development planning|author=Oldham Metropolitan Borough Council|publisher=oldham.gov.uk|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> United Utilities manages Chadderton's [[drinking water|drinking]] and [[waste water]].<ref name="UU"/> Water supplies are sourced from several reservoirs in the borough, including [[Dovestones Reservoir|Dovestones]] and [[Chew Reservoir, Greater Manchester|Chew]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/?OBH=445&ID=3526 |title=Dove Stone Reservoirs|publisher=unitedutilities.com|author=[[United Utilities]]|date=2007-04-17|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> A [[sewage treatment]] works is located in the southwest of Chadderton, at Foxdenton. It opened in 1898.<ref name="Plan"/>

A [[power station]] in Chadderton existed in as early as 1925, built for the [[County Borough of Oldham]] in the Slacks Valley.<ref name="CLR">{{citation |url=http://www.eugris.info/envdocs/CLR03_00.pdf|format=PDF|title=Documentary Research on Industrial Sites: CLR Report 3|publisher=eugris.info|author=[[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]]|year=1994|accessdate=2010-01-28}}</ref> This structure was demolished to make way for the new [[Chadderton Power Station|Chadderton "B" Power Station]], opened in 1955 for the [[British Electricity Authority]] in anticipation that the region would experience increased demand for electricity.<ref>{{citation |title=India-Rubber Journal|volume=125|date=July-December 1953|page=291}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/159619/power%20stations%20in%20greater%20manchester.pdf|format=PDF|title=Power Stations in Greater Manchester|publisher=msim.org.uk|author=[[Museum of Science and Industry in Manchester]]|year=2001|accessdate=2008-12-23}}</ref> Structural changes to the [[National Grid (UK)|National Grid]] made the power station redundant in 1982.<ref name="Chadderton73">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=73}}.</ref> It was sold by the [[Central Electricity Generating Board]] in 1984, and demolished in 1986.<ref name="CLR"/><ref name="Chadderton2">{{Harvnb|Lawson|Johnson|1997|p=2}}.</ref> Chadderton's [[Distribution Network Operator]] for electricity is United Utilities.<ref name="UU">{{citation |url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/?OBH=4188&ID=1442|title=Oldham|publisher=unitedutilities.com|author=United Utilities|date=2007-04-17|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref>

==Notable people==
{{seealso|List of people from Oldham}}
People from Chadderton are called Chaddertonians. Historically, Chadderton was chiefly distinguished by the presence of [[manorialism|ruling families]], including the Asshetons, Radclyffes, Hortons and Chaddertons. Within the extended Chadderton/Chaderton family, two ecclesiastically notable persons were [[William Chaderton]] (medieval academic and bishop) and [[Laurence Chaderton]] (one of the original translators of the [[Authorized King James Version|Authorised King James Version of the Bible]]).<ref name="Looking5"/> John Ashton of Cowhill and Thomas Buckley of Baretrees in Chadderton were two victims of the [[Peterloo Massacre]] in 1819.<ref name="Chadderton8"/><ref name="County of Lancs"/> [[Lydia Becker]] was a leader within Britain's 19th-century [[suffragette]] movement, born in Chadderton's Foxdenton Hall.<ref name="SpinWeb">{{citation |url=http://www.spinningtheweb.org.uk/m_display.php?irn=239&sub=nwcotton&theme=places&crumb=Oldham|publisher=spinningtheweb.org.uk|author=[[Manchester City Council]]|title=Oldham|accessdate=2008-12-20}}</ref> Chadderton born scientist Geoff Tootill helped create the [[Manchester Small-Scale Experimental Machine]] in 1948, the world's first electronic stored-program computer.<ref>{{citation |title=Baby changed the world |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/technology/s/1054840_baby_changed_the_world |author=Paul Taylor |work=Manchester Evening News |date=2008-06-20 |accessdate=2008-08-20}}</ref> [[Terry Hall (ventriloquist)|Terry Hall]] was a pioneering ventriloquist and early children<U+2019>s television entertainer born in Chadderton in 1926.<ref name="Terry1">{{citation |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article1652124.ece|publisher=timesonline.co.uk|date= 2007-04-14|accessdate=2008-12-20|title=Terry Hall: Pioneering ventriloquist who turned a variety act into a television institution for all the family | location=London}}</ref><ref name="Terry2">{{citation |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1548316/Terry-Hall.html|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|date=2007-04-12|title=Terry Hall|accessdate=2008-12-20}}</ref> He was one of the first ventriloquists to perform with an animal (the "cowardly and bashful" Lenny the Lion) as his puppet, rather than a traditional child doll.<ref name="Terry1"/><ref name="Terry2"/> Other notable people from Chadderton include [[Woolly Wolstenholme]], the Chadderton-born vocalist and keyboard player with the British progressive rock band [[Barclay James Harvest]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bjharvest.co.uk/bjh-biog.htm|publisher=bjharvest.co.uk|title=Barclay James Harvest Biography|accessdate=2008-12-20}}</ref> [[David Platt (footballer)|David Platt]], former captain of the [[England national football team]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/article798814.ece|publisher=timesonline.co.uk|last=Kay|first=Oliver|title=The error that let Henry slip through United net|date=2002-12-06|accessdate=2009-01-02 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050312021903/http://www.thefa.com/Features/EnglishDomestic/Postings/2003/06/54182.htm|publisher=thefa.com|title=Englishmen Abroad: David Platt|last=Wright|first=James|accessdate=2009-09-11|author=The Football Association|authorlink=The Football Association|work=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.givemefootball.com/player-profiles/david-platt|publisher=givemefootball.com|title=David Platt Profile|accessdate=2008-12-20}}</ref> and supermodel [[Karen Elson]], who grew up in the town and attended [[North Chadderton School]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.northchaddertonschool.co.uk/index.php?id=79|publisher=northchaddertonschool.co.uk|title=North Chadderton Sixth Form |accessdate=2009-09-11|author=North Chadderton School}}</ref><ref name="Borough Oldhamer">{{citation |title=A supermodel pupil drops in at her old school|newspaper=The Borough Oldhamer|publisher=|pages=3|date=June/July 2005 | issue =26}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/13820/chaddertons-karen-is-the-new-face-of-john-lewis|publisher=oldham-chronicle.co.uk|title=Chadderton<U+2019>s Karen is the new face of John Lewis|accessdate=2008-12-29|date=2008-09-09|last=Barker|first=Janice}}</ref>

